President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring April 14, 2016, as Pan American Day and April 10 through April 16, 2016, as Pan American Week. The proclamation recognizes the Organization of American States, founded in the late 19th century, and the 15th anniversary of the Inter-American Democratic Charter. The proclamation highlights the progress made in the Western Hemisphere through increased integration, trade partnerships, and cooperation on issues such as clean energy and climate change. It also acknowledges the reestablishment of diplomatic relations between the United States and Cuba, as well as the President's visit to Argentina. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of engaging with the Americas and working together to address challenges such as violence, peacekeeping, the Zika virus, and economic growth. The President calls for unity and cooperation among the nations of the Americas to create a future of peace, dignity, and opportunity for all. The proclamation encourages governors and officials across the United States to honor these observances with appropriate ceremonies and activities.